        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(telegram): preserve persistent rich message line breaks",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nFixes #95409.\n\nTelegram persistent rich messages can collapse ordinary final-answer line breaks when `richMessages` is enabled. The plain `sendMessage` path preserves a normal assistant reply like:\n\n```text\n第一行\n第二行\n第三行\n```\n\nbut the Bot API 10.1 persistent rich-message path sends `rich_message.html`, where literal text-node `\\n` is not a reliable visual line break. This makes structured replies look compressed even though the account explicitly opted into rich messages.\n\nThis PR fixes the supported persistent rich-message path only. It does **not** use `sendRichMessageDraft`, does not change native draft streaming behavior, and does not introduce an extra final message bubble.\n\n## Summary\n\n- Preserve text-node line breaks during Telegram rich HTML preparation.\n- Convert ordinary non-whitespace text-node `\\n` to `<br>` before sending `rich_message.html`.\n- Leave pure structural whitespace between tags unchanged.\n- Leave newlines inside `<pre>` / `<code>` literal.\n- Add regression tests for rich final-message line breaks and preformatted/code blocks.\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\nThe previous preparation path only sanitized rich HTML and enforced Telegram's nesting limit:\n\n```ts\nfunction prepareTelegramRichHtml(html: string): string {\n  return limitTelegramRichHtmlNesting(sanitizeTelegramRichHtml(html), TELEGRAM_RICH_NESTING_LIMIT);\n}\n```\n\nThe new helper runs after sanitization and before nesting-limit enforcement. It walks HTML tags, tracks `<pre>` / `<code>` depth, and only materializes newlines in non-whitespace text nodes. That keeps existing HTML structure and code/preformatted content stable while making normal assistant text readable in Telegram Rich Messages.\n\n## Evidence\n\nSource-level reproduction on latest `openclaw/openclaw` main checked at `955f3ed09465f0a475776335c2fe205ef84d6a85`:\n\n- `extensions/telegram/src/rich-message.ts` prepared `rich_message.html` with sanitize + nesting limit only.\n- No existing code path materialized ordinary text-node newlines as `<br>` for persistent rich final messages.\n- The affected path is `sendRichMessage` / `editMessageText({ rich_message })`, not `sendRichMessageDraft`.\n\nLocal lightweight validation after rebasing onto latest `upstream/main` (`955f3ed09465f0a475776335c2fe205ef84d6a85`):\n\n```text\ngit diff --check\n# passed\n\ngit diff -- extensions/telegram/src | grep -q 'sendRichMessageDraft'\n# no sendRichMessageDraft changes\n```\n\nRegression coverage added:\n\n- `preserves plain line breaks in native rich final messages`\n- `keeps preformatted rich HTML newlines literal`\n\nReal Telegram behavior observed in a direct chat with `richMessages` enabled:\n\n- ordinary final reply line breaks were readable through the plain `sendMessage` path;\n- the persistent rich-message path could visually compress ordinary line-separated text;\n- a candidate patch restored the expected line breaks while still using `sendRichMessage` with `rich_message.html`;\n- inspected outbound payload shape used `sendRichMessage` and had ordinary text line breaks materialized as `<br>`.\n\nI did not run the full local test suite in this worktree because dependencies were not installed locally; GitHub Actions should be treated as the authoritative validation gate for this OpenClaw PR.\n\n## Risk / Rollback\n\nRisk is limited to Telegram accounts that opted into rich messages. The change is conservative because it only affects text nodes that contain non-whitespace content and avoids preformatted/code blocks.\n\nRollback: revert this PR to return rich HTML preparation to sanitize + nesting limit only.\n\n",
        "branch": "fix/telegram-rich-linebreaks-persistent",
